John Mason (The Rock) <br />
Draco (Dragonheart) <br />
Marko Ramius (Hunt for Red October)<br />
Jim Malone (Untouchables)<br />
Alan Quatermaine (The League of Extraordinary Gentlemen)<br />
<br />
Please tell me which of these characters that he plays has any REAL weakness as a human being besides losing a swordfight that he, by the nature of the movie (Highlander) has to lose. The closest is Marko Ramius in Hunt for Red October, but this is American film for American audiences, so his struggle in his defection to the Soviet Union is perceived in America is not much of a struggle at all. To us, he&#39;s just a reformed villain becoming a good guy. <br />
<br />
So either a) Sean Connery is a good actor, but chooses to be an old, Welsh version of basically Sylvester Stallone or Chuck Norris, or b) He&#39;s a bad actor that can&#39;t show vulnerability or negative aspects of a character because he isn&#39;t good at conveying emotions other than being a hard ass. <br><BR><font size=1>13:00 09-18-2012</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>boothwah </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=boothwah '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">On Mckellan - There is no way Connery could have held a torch - THE MOMENT of FOTR that made that whole series magic was the scene at the council of Rivendell - Where they are all arguing - Bam! Close up of Gandalf&#39;s face as Frodo says "I will take the ring" in the background......money.<br />
